Subject: definition
Value: <2012-04-05: Barry SmithThe official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions' is terrible.Can you fix to something like:A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.Alan RuttenbergYour proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. On the specifics of the proposed definition:We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with. @en>

Subject: serous membrane
Value: multi-tissue structure that is comprised of a secretory epithelial layer (mesothelium) and a connective tissue layer.

Subject: post-embryonic stage
Value: stage succeeding embryo, including mature structure

Subject: lung connective tissue
Value: the connective tissue located between the respiratory (airway and alveolar) epithelium, the capillary endothelium and pleural mesothelium; it contains basement membrane composed of collagen, elastin, proteoglycans, and fibronectin

Subject: cornea
Value: the transparent anterior portion of the fibrous coat of the eye that serves as the chief refractory structure

Subject: circulatory system
Value: organ system that passes nutrients (such as amino acids and electrolytes), gases, hormones, blood cells, etc. to and from cells in the body to help fight diseases and help stabilize body temperature and pH to maintain homeostasis[WP].

Subject: anterior chamber of eyeball
Value: the space in the eye, filled with aqueous humor, and bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and part of the crystalline lens

Subject: uvea
Value: the pigmented middle of the three concentric layers that make up an eye, consisting of the iris, ciliary body and choroid[WP,edited].

Subject: iris
Value: the adjustable membrane, composed of the stroma and pigmented epithelium, located just in front of the crystalline lens within the eye

Subject: corneal epithelium
Value: the smooth stratified squamous epithelium that covers the outer surface of the cornea

Subject: ciliary body
Value: the thickened portion of the vascular tunic, which lies between the choroid and the iris, composed of ciliary muscle and ciliary processes

Subject: optic choroid
Value: vascular layer containing connective tissue, of the eye lying between the retina and the sclera. The choroid provides oxygen and nourishment to the outer layers of the retina. Along with the ciliary body and iris, the choroid forms the uveal tract[WP].

Subject: anterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in front of, or ventral to, the lens (inclusive)

Subject: posterior segment of eyeball
Value: any of the parts of the eye that lie in back of, or dorsal to, the lens (but not inclusive)

Subject: capsule of lens
Value: the elastic, clear, membrane-like structure, that is outer most layer of the lens

Subject: myocardium of atrium
Value: the atrial part of middle layer of the heart, comprised of involuntary muscle

Subject: epicardium
Value: a region of the serous membrane that forms the innermost layer of the pericardium and the outer surface of the heart.

Subject: myocardium
Value: the middle layer of the heart, comprised mainly of striated cardiac muscle fibers

Subject: pericardial sac
Value: a double-walled sac containing the heart and the roots of the great vessels.

Subject: gland
Value: an organ that functions as a secretory or excretory organ

Subject: cranial neural crest
Value: neural crest cells (NCCs) originating in the anterior part of the developing embryo and residing between the mid-diencephalon and the forming hindbrain; cranial NCCs migrate dorsolaterally to form the craniofacial mesenchyme that differentiates into various craniofacial cartilages and bones, cranial neurons, glia, and connective tissues of the face; these cells enter the pharyngeal pouches and arches where they give rise to thymic cells, bones of the middle ear and jaw (mandible), and the odontoblasts of the tooth primordia; like their counterparts in the trunk, cranial NCCs also contribute to the developing peripheral nervous system, along with the pigmented cell (i.e. melanocyte) lineage.

Subject: smooth muscle of eye
Value: <any of the striated muscles that move the eye and include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, lateral rectus, superior oblique, inferior oblique, retractor bulbi>

Subject: aorta smooth muscle tissue
Value: the nonstriated, involuntary muscle tissue located in the wall of the aorta

Subject: blood vessel smooth muscle
Value: smooth muscle found within, and composing the majority of the wall of blood vessels.

Subject: aorta tunica adventitia
Value: the outermost layer of the aorta wall, containing connective tissue and collagen and elastic fibers

Subject: bulbus cordis
Value: a transient fetal dilation of the distal (or cranial) heart tube located where the arterial trunk joins the ventral roots of the aortic arches

Subject: respiratory system mucosa
Value: the mucous membrane lining the respiratory tract

Subject: respiratory tract epithelium
Value: the pseudostratified ciliated epithelium that lines much of the conducting portion of the airway, including part of the nasal cavity and larynx, the trachea, and bronchi

Subject: aorta endothelium
Value: the thin layer of flat cells that line the aorta and form a barrier between circulating blood in the lumen and the rest of the vessel wall

Subject: mandibular prominence
Value: the paired ventral prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo; the two prominences unite ventrally and fuse to form the mandible and lower lip

Subject: corneo-scleral junction
Value: the edge of the cornea where it joins the sclera; the limbus is a common site for the occurrence of corneal epithelial neoplasm

Subject: pigment epithelium of eye
Value: epithelial layer of the retina, ciliary body, or iris composed of cells containing pigment granules.

Subject: cavity of left atrium

Subject: cavity of left ventricle
Value: luminal space of the left ventricle of the heart.

Subject: cavity of right atrium
Value: luminal space of the right atrium of the heart.

Subject: prechordal mesoderm
Value: the area of axial mesoderm that develops into the prechordal plate

Subject: wall of heart
Value: wall of organ which has as its parts the endocardium, myocardium , epicardium, and the cardiac septum, surrounded by the pericardial sac proper and is continuous with the walls of the systemic and pulmonary arterial and venous trees.

Subject: predatory behavior abnormal

Subject: reduced predatory feeding behavior
Value: (Pristionchus pacificus) Animals exhibit reduced predatory feeding behavior, indicated by reduced predation success, compared to controls.

Subject: Lineage

Subject: epithelial cell

In C. elegans epithelial cells include epithelium of the alimentary tract, intestinal cells, hypodermis, interfacial cells and somatic gonad cells.

Subject: marginal cell
Value: a type of pharyngeal cell that connects basement membrane to the apices of triangle-shaped pharyngeal lumen.

Subject: muscle cell
Value: contractile cell that makes up muscle tissue.

Subject: pharynx
Value: the feeding organ, a neuro-muscular pump in the head of the animal, used to ingest food, bacteria suspended in liquid, filter them out, grind them up and transport posteriorly into the instestine.

Subject: terminal bulb
Value: the last, posterior bulb of the pharynx.

Subject: corpus
Value: the first, anterior bulb of the pharynx.

Subject: isthmus
Value: a section of pharynx of which muscles contract with a peristaltic motion.

Subject: organ
Value: a collection of cells or cell groups that collectively perform a function

Subject: Cell
Value: a cellular object that consists of subcellular components, expresses genes or functions.

Subject: anchor cell
Value: anchor cell, induces vulva, part of hermaphrodite gonad.

Subject: excretory duct cell
Value: cell that forms the duct of the excretory system.

Subject: linker cell
Value: male gonad cell, leads gonad during morphogenesis and initiates union with cloaca

Subject: labial sensillum
Value: sensillum of inner or outer labial.

Subject: inner labial sensillum
Value: sensory organ of the inner labial.

Subject: gonad
Value: organ producing either sperm or ova.

Subject: GLR
Value: set of six cells that form a thin cylindrical sheet between pharynx and ring neuropile; no chemical synapses, but gap junctions with muscle arms and RME motor neurons, might be glial cells

Subject: hermaphrodite gonad
Value: organ in hermaphrodite animal that produces both ova and sperm.

Subject: dorso-rectal ganglion
Value: the ganglion that lies above and behind the rectum in the tail, in close continuity with the anal hypodermal ridge. It contains 3 neuron cell bodies (DVA, DVB and DVC) that send their neuronal processes into the ventral nerve cord via dorso-rectal commissures that encircle the anus. The ganglion contains no local neuropil in the hermaphrodite. In the adult male tail, this ganglion gains additional neurons and some local neuropil.

Subject: dorsal ganglion
Value: ganglion that lies beside the nerve ring in the head. It contains neuron cell bodies that send their neuronal processes into the ring and longitudinal nerves, but form no local neuropil separate from the nerve ring. The dorsal ganglion is in close contact with the dorsal hypodermal cord.

Subject: touch receptor neuron
Value: neurons that sense body touch, have specialized microtubules in processes.

Subject: buccal cavity
Value: cuticle-lined lumenal region surrounded by pharyngeal epithelium, situated at the anterior end of pharynx.

Subject: ventral ganglion
Value: ganglion lies beside the nerve ring in the head, just anterior of the retrovesicular ganglion. It contains about 20 interneuron and motorneuron cell bodies that all send their neuronal processes into the ring. The cell bodies are divided into two groups by the intrusion of the excretory duct and canal. The cells are bounded by a basal lamina which physically separates them from the lateral ganglion even though they are adjacent to one another.

Subject: spermatheca
Value: an accordion-like tube that contains sperm and is the site of oocyte fertilization.

Subject: body ganglion
Value: ganglion in the trunk of the body.

Subject: uterine muscle
Value: muscle lining of the uterine wall.

Subject: anterior ganglion
Value: ganglion anterior to the nerve ring

Subject: motor neuron
Value: neuron making synapse on an effector (muscle, gland).

Subject: phasmid sensillum
Value: bilateral sensory organ in the tail, similar to the amphid in the head.

Subject: phasmid left sensillum
Value: the left one in the pair of phasmid sensilla.

Subject: pharyngeal muscle cell
Value: type of cells that make up muscle layers in the pharynx.

Subject: posterior lateral ganglion
Value: ganglion on the lateral side, in postior portion of the body, associated with posterior deirid.

Subject: epithelial system
Value: lies within the body wall, in close relation to nervous system and excretory system.

Subject: muscular system
Value: the organ system that allows the animal move, includes all muscles.

Subject: body region
Value: region of the body by which tissues, cells or cell parts are classified

Subject: head
Value: anterior-most body region containing the pharynx.

Subject: midbody
Value: body region posterior to the head and anterior to the tail

Subject: tail
Value: posterior region, from rectum to the end

Subject: digestive tract
Value: inner tube of two concentric tubes that make up the body

Subject: Organ system
Value: intergrated group of organs, performing one or more unified functions.

Subject: Sex specific entity
Value: anatomical or cell objects that exist in only one, male or hermaphrodite, sex.

Subject: seam cell
Value: a group of hypodermal cells that lie along the apical midline of the hypodermis, at the extreme left and right sides between nose and tail

Subject: interfacial epithelial cell
Value: an epithelial cell that serves either to bridge two neighboring epithelial tissues or to form an opening in the epithelium.

Subject: cuticle
Value: a rigid external coating which is secreted by the hypodermis, seam and some transitional epithelial cells which covers the outer body, the major openings  into the body cavity from the exterior, and two large sensory bristles, the male spicules.  The cuticle of the spicules, the hook,  and of some portions of the spicule channels is especially rigid and is probably sclerotized.  Similar sclerotic features are occasionally noted in the ventral surface of the male tail fan.

Subject: male-specific anatomical entity
Value: cells or anatomical parts specific to the male sex

Subject: hermaphrodite-specific anatomical entity
Value: cells or anatomical parts specific to the hermaphrodite sex

Subject: sensory neuron
Value: neuron that senses external stimuli and transduce them to signals internal to the organism.

Subject: accessory cell
Value: cells that support sensory neurons, similar to glial cells in vertebrates. A category which collectively refers to socket cells, sheath cells, and structural cells, or their processes.  All of these cells extend long processes which serve a supporting role, rather like glia, to form a protective environment around sensory neuron endings.  In addition, some of these cells extend broad thin processes from their somata which wrap around neuronal ganglia, again in a glia-like fashion

Subject: Functional system
Value: concerns with functional aspects of cells and anatomical parts

Subject: Anatomy
Value: entity of anatomical origin that is either entirely acellular or is a collection of cells and acellular parts.

Subject: cloaca
Value: a feature of the male tail, caudal to the proctodeum, where the vas deferens and the intestine open out jointly near the tail tip to discharge their contents.

Subject: excretory gland cell
Value: gland cell of the secretory-excretory system, sends processes to ring, opens into excretory duct.

Subject: germ line
Value: cell line which early in development becomes differentiated from the remaining somatic cell line, and alone has the potential to undergo meiosis and form gametes.

Subject: intestinal cell
Value: any of 20 large epithelial cells which form a tube and are mostly situated as bilaterally symmetric pairs around the tubular lumen. Each of these cell pairs forms an intestinal ring ( II-IX int rings). The most anterior intestinal ring (int ring I), however, is made of four cells. Intestinal cells contain large nuclei with large nucleoli and numerous autofluorescent granules in their cytoplasm.

Subject: neuronal sheath cell
Value: a structural (glial) cell which forms an specialized environment surrounding the sensory ending(s) of one or more neurons; sometimes accompanied by a more distal socket cell.  In early development of the sensory nerves and of the nerve ring some sheath cells (cephalics and labials) may also provide a substrate for axon guidance

Subject: alimentary muscle
Value: muscle of the alimentary organ system.

Subject: gonadal sheath cell
Value: five pairs of thin gonadal sheath cells form a single layer covering the germ line component of each arm, each pair occupying a stereotyped position along the gonad proximal-distal axis.

Subject: ventral nerve cord
Value: a large process bundle that runs along the vental mid-line extending from the ventral region of the nerve ring.

Subject: nerve ring
Value: the most extensive region of neuropil in the animal, consists of a large toroidal bundle of processes.

Subject: dorsal nerve cord
Value: a bundle of nerve processes that runs along the dorsal mid-line of the animal.

Subject: head muscle
Value: body wall muscle in the head, including first eight cells of each muscle quadrants which are innervated by nerve ring neurons.

Subject: blast cell
Value: precursor cell destined to divide some time after hatching.

Subject: uterine-vulval cell
Value: monoucleate interfacial cell between the uterus and vulva (uv1-uv3), four sets total (L/R, A/P)

Subject: male gonad
Value: gonad of a male animal, produces sperm.

Subject: germ cell
Value: a cell, of either sex, directly concerned in the production of a new organism.

Subject: body wall muscle cell
Value: type of 95 cells that make up muscles of the body wall.

Subject: ciliated neuron
Value: neuron type, neurons that have ciliated nerve endings.

Subject: serotonergic neuron
Value: neuron that uses serotonin as a vesicular neurotransmitter.

Subject: cholinergic neuron
Value: neuron that uses vesicular acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter.

Subject: germline precursor cell
Value: member of a set of two cells that generate exclusively sperm and ovum.

Subject: distal tip cell
Value: somatic cell that situates at the tip of a gonad arm.

Subject: seminal vesicle
Value: part of male gonad that holds mature sperm, made of a total of 12 nuclei.

Subject: gubernacular muscle
Value: specialized muscle type in male sex organ.

Subject: longitudinal male muscle
Value: specialized muscle type in the posterior of adult male.

Subject: cephalic sensillum
Value: sensillum in the head, each with a CEP receptor neuron.

Subject: sensillum
Value: sensory organ, consists of sensory neurons and supporting cells.

Subject: ray
Value: male sensory organ; nine bilateral pairs of finger-like rays (numbered 1 to 9, Left/Right) radiate from the tail and are embedded in a cuticlar fan.

Subject: tail ganglion
Value: ganglion in the tail region (posterior to rectum).

Subject: embryonic cell
Value: cell that exists in and is part of an embryo.

Subject: post-embryonic cell
Value: a cell that is born in a worm after hatching.

Subject: vulval precursor cell
Value: cell that has the potential to form structural part of a vulva.

Subject: body muscle cell
Value: any muscle cell that is not pharyngeal.

Subject: hermaphrodite somatic gonadal cell
Value: somatic (not germline) cell of the hermaphrodite gonad.

Subject: hypodermal cell
Value: primary cell type that forms the hypodermis.

Subject: syncytium precursor
Value: cell that is mononuclear and has a strong potential to fuse with other cell(s) to form a multinucleated cell.

Subject: syncytium
Value: cell that has more than one nucleus.

Subject: seminal vesical cell
Value: seminal vesicle cell of male gonad.

Subject: gon_male_sves Z1 or Z4
Value: seminal vesicle, outer; cell of the pedigree Z1.paapp or Z4.aaapp.

Subject: vulval syncytia precursor
Value: precursor cell of, before fusion to form vulval syncytia vulA(4), vulC(4), vulD(2), vulE(4) and vulF(4).

Subject: sex organ
Value: anatomical part of the body which is involved in sexual reproduction and constitutes the reproductive system.

Subject: male genital
Value: antomical structure of the male involved in sexual reproduction.

Subject: mechanosensory neuron
Value: neuron that senses and responds to mechanical stimuli, such as touch.

Subject: uterine epithelial cell
Value: cell of the epithelia of uterus.

Subject: decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to
Value: q1 decreased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) < magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: different_in_magnitude_relative_to
Value: q1 different_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) NOT =~ magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: has_cross_section
Value: <s3 has_cross_section s3 if and only if : there exists some 2d plane that intersects the bearer of s3, and the impression of s3 upon that plane has shape quality s2.>

Subject: increased_in_magnitude_relative_to
Value: q1 increased_in_magnitude_relative_to q2 if and only if magnitude(q1) > magnitude(q2). Here, magnitude(q) is a function that maps a quality to a unit-invariant scale.

Subject: reciprocal_of
Value: <q1 reciprocal_of q2 if and only if : q1 and q2 are relational qualities and a phenotype e q1 e2 mutually implies a phenotype e2 q2 e.>

Subject: anteriorly connected to
Value: x anteriorly_connected_to y iff the anterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x posterior_to y.

Subject: conduit for
Value: x is a conduit for y iff y passes through the lumen of x.

Subject: posteriorly connected to
Value: x posteriorly_connected_to y iff the posterior part of x is connected to y. i.e. x connected_to y and x anterior_to y.
